16 (1) Artificial intelligence ("AI"), the development of computer systems to perform tasks
17 that normally require human intelligence, such as learning and decision making, has the
18 potential to spur innovation and transform industry and government;
19 (2) As the science and technology of AI continue to develop, more products and services
20 are utilizing AI in fields such as healthcare, financial services, education, housing, and
21 transportation. Such utilization may ultimately displace certain jobs and fields of
22 employment;
23 (3) There are valid concerns about potential misuse or unintended consequences of AI,
24 especially without the development and implementation of ethical standards that seek to
25 preserve the dignity, autonomy, and self-determination of individuals;
26 (4) In the 2023 legislative session, at least 25 states, Puerto Rico, and the District of
27 Columbia introduced AI bills, and 18 states and Puerto Rico adopted resolutions or enacted
28 legislation in this area; and
29 (5) It is important that this state establish policies and procedures concerning the
30 development, procurement, implementation, utilization, and ongoing assessment of systems
31 that employ AI and are in use by state agencies.
32 SECTION 3.
33 Chapter 1 of Title 50 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated, relating to general
34 provisions regarding state government, is amended by adding a new Code section to read as
35 follows:
36 "50-1-14.
37 (a) As used in this Code section, the term:
38 (1) 'Artificial intelligence system' or 'AI system' means an engineered or machine based
39 system that emulates the capability of a person to receive audio, visual, text, or any other
40 form of information and use the information received to emulate a human cognitive
41 process, including, but not limited to, learning, generalizing, reasoning, planning,
