42 predicting, acting, or communicating; provided, however, that artificial intelligence
43 systems may vary in the forms of information they can receive and in the human
44 cognitive processes they can emulate.
45 (2) 'Governmental entity' means any department, agency, board, bureau, commission,
46 authority, county, municipal corporation, school system, or other political subdivision of
47 this state.
48 (b) Each governmental entity shall be required to publish by December 31, 2026, on a
49 public website, and thereafter maintain, a comprehensive artificial intelligence system
50 usage plan, which shall, at a minimum, include the following:
51 (1) Specific goals and objectives for AI system deployment, including the benefits the
52 governmental entity aims to achieve;
53 (2) Steps taken by the governmental entity to avoid bias and ensure fairness across
54 diverse user groups;
55 (3) Data privacy measures implemented in the use of AI systems, including data storage
56 and collection protocols;
57 (4) Roles and responsibilities for AI system governance within the governmental entity;
58 (5) Details of compliance with relevant laws;
59 (6) The role of human oversight in AI system processes;
60 (7) Training programs for employees of such governmental entity on the safe and ethical
61 use of AI systems;
62 (8) Protocols for incident response in case of AI system malfunctions, biases, or
63 breaches; and
64 (9) Reporting procedures for AI system related incidents to affected authorities and
65 parties."
